results.name: 720 Hilgard Apartments
results.text_description: Completed in 2010, this is a LEED Silver certified building. The three former Hilgard Avenue sorority houses were redeveloped into two apartment complexes designed for single graduate housing. These new facilities opened in September 2010. One complex, located at 720 Hilgard, consists of 54 studio apartments, and the other, located at 824 Hilgard, consists of 29 studio apartments. All units are furnished. Each apartment has a kitchen with a refrigerator, stove, microwave, dishwasher, and garbage disposal. In addition, each apartment comes with central heating and air conditioning, UCLA Wi-Fi, campus telephone system, campus basic cable, campus high-speed Internet access, flat-screen TV, mini blinds, and 24-hour emergency maintenance. Each apartment building has a uniquely landscaped courtyard, a common study/social lounge with a 60-inch large screen TV, a common laundry facility, and gated parking. Both buildings are handicapped accessible.

Due to the limits and rarity of resources in Asian American Studies, there is no circulation of materials. However, a self-use photocopier in the library is available. results.name: Aloe Court Apartments
results.text_description: Part of the newly-established Weyburn Terrace Housing Complex, Aloe Court provides on-campus housing for graduate students. Development of the Southwest campus site began in 2003 and was completed in May 2005. Weyburn Terrace Phase I is a Mediterranean-style apartment complex consisting of 840 furnished studios, two-bedroom/two-bath apartments, and two-bedroom/two-bath townhouses. Each apartment building has a uniquely landscaped courtyard, a common study lounge, a common laundry facility, covered parking and is handicapped accessible. There is a central barbecue area. Each apartment has a kitchen with a refrigerator, stove, microwave, dishwasher, and garbage disposal. results.name: Amtrak California Thruway Bus Stop
results.text_description: Amtrak California's Westwood/UCLA Thruway is a dedicated bus connection to San Joaquin and Pacific Surfliner trains, making Amtrak train travel seamless, easy and economical. It's a short walk from UCLA Residence Halls to get to Central Valley destinations including Fresno and Sacramento, as well as the San Francisco Bay Area, or travel the coast to places like Santa Barbara or San Luis Obispo. With your reservation, simply board an Amtrak California Thruway bus at 592 Gayley Avenue at Strathmore Drive, travel non-stop to the Van Nuys or Bakersfield Amtrak stations and connect with your train. There are four UCLA departures and arrivals daily.

results.name: Botanical Garden
results.text_description: The Mildred E. Mathias Botanical Garden (MEMBG) is a living museum, having special collections designed to assist the undergraduate teaching mission at UCLA and to augment the capability for research on campus. MEMBG serves as a long-term repository for unusual plants, a refugium for biodiversity. This facility offers its educational content to the campus community, residents of Los Angeles, and visitors from around the world to enhance learning about plants and promote greater appreciation for relevance of plants to society.

results.name: Botanical Garden La Kretz Entrance
results.text_description: The newest entrance to the Mildred E. Mathias Botanical Garden was made possible by a generous donation from Morton La Kretz, real estate developer, philanthropist, and UCLA alumnus. The new entrance to the seven-acre botanical garden is the first step in a series of renovations to increase the garden's visibility, upgrade its infrastructure, improve its accessibility for the disabled and make it an increased focal point for visitors to UCLA. La Kretz remembers, as a UCLA undergraduate, gathering "swampy" water from the garden for a biology class experiment. Years later, he traveled to Costa Rica on a popular field-study tour led by renowned scientist and horticulturist Mildred Mathias, for whom the garden is named and who served as its director from 1956 to 1974.

results.name: Boyer Hall

results.name: Bridges Theater
results.text_description: Named in honor of film director James Bridges (The China Syndrome), the theater become one of the outstanding screening venues in Southern California, due to the generous support of the filmmaker's partner, actor Jack Larson, and the Bridges/Larson Foundation. The main screening venue of the UCLA Department of Film, Television and Digital Media, the state of the art James Bridges Theater is an elegant, comfortable setting that enhances media presentations in a wide variety of film and video formats. With a large lobby available for receptions, and adjacent to the beautiful Broad Art Complex and the famous Murphy Sculpture Garden on the UCLA campus in Westwood, this 278 seat theater is now available for rental. It was completely renovated in 2003 with a state of the art sound system and is one of the few theaters in the US that can accommodate both nitrate and safety film stock in 16mm, 35mm and 70mm, as well as a variety of video formats, including the latest in 4K digital projection.

After serving in WWII in the Marine Corp from 1943 to 1945, Briskin graduated from what is now UCLA Anderson School of Management with a BS in business administration. He went on to grow Gelson's Markets into one of the most prestigious grocery store chains in Southern California.

Opened in Fall 2013, the 900-seat Bruin Plate offers a menu that focuses on fresh, wholesome, and nutritionally-balanced options and follows best practices of sustainability in food service operations. Bruin Plate offers fresh, delicious and wholesome food in an environment that supports "mindful eating." Bruin Plate creates a dining experience that encourages you to pay attention to what you eat—using your senses to explore, savor, and taste—and to choose food that is both pleasing to you and nourishing to your body.

results.name: Center for Health Sciences
results.text_description: The UCLA Center for Health Sciences is the home of the David Geffen School of Medicine. On May 7, 2002 entertainment executive and philanthropist David Geffen announced a $200 million unrestricted gift to the School of Medicine. The gift is the largest ever made to the University of California, and the largest single donation ever made to a school of medicine in this country. In recognition, the school now bears Geffen's name.

results.name: Center for the Art of Performance at UCLA
results.text_description: Center for the Art of Performance at UCLA (CAP UCLA) is dedicated to the advancement of the contemporary performing arts in all disciplines dance, music, spoken word and theater, as well the emerging digital, collaborative and cross-art platforms inspired by today's leading artists and creators. CAP supports the creation, presentation and critical dialogues vital to the ongoing innovation and expressive potential of artists whose work, whether vibrantly emerging or internationally acclaimed, forms the dynamic and evolving heritage of contemporary performance. Based in UCLA's iconic Royce Hall, CAP UCLA is the university's public center for the presentation of the performing arts and contributes to the cultural life of the campus and greater Los Angeles, promoting civic dialogue and creative inquiry. Through an annual season of performing arts programs and extensive community-engagement events including artist fellows and residency programs, K-12 arts education (Design for Sharing), student mentorship (Student Committee for the Arts), and art-making and experiential activities (Art in Action) CAP UCLA advances the importance of art in society by celebrating and deepening the connection between artist and audience. CAP UCLA is the recent evolution of the organization most recently known as UCLA Live. In CAP UCLA's inaugural 2012-2013 season, we celebrate 75 years of performing arts presentation on the UCLA campus. Since 1937 Royce Hall and surrounding campus venues have been home to a veritable Who's-Who from every performing arts discipline. We are proud to carry on and build upon this great history with a reinvigorated commitment to connecting Los Angeles audiences with the artists who are pushing the culture and dialogue of our times.

results.name: Center for World Languages
results.text_description: The UCLA Center for World Languages (CWL) coordinates language research, teaching and evaluation programs. The Center develops innovative methods of second language education, advocates for their implementation, and facilitates their transfer into formal classrooms and informal settings. CWL offers programs in partnership with other campus departments and schools, and with public and private institutions throughout the USA and abroad.

results.name: Coach John Wooden Statue
results.text_description: The statue was created by renowned sculptor Blair Buswell, who has crafted likenesses of a variety of famous sports figures for major sports venues, including more than 68 busts of inductees into the Pro Football Hall of Fame and statues of prominent athletes and coaches, among them Jack Nicklaus, Oscar Robertson and Paul "Bear" Bryant. Buswell worked on the project for nearly one year, consulting with the Wooden family and UCLA representatives along the way to ensure that the artwork would be as authentic and true to Wooden's demeanor as possible. Wooden's storied 27 seasons (1948-1979) as UCLA Head Basketball Coach included seven consecutive NCAA championships between 1967 and 1973, and 10 titles in his final 12 seasons as head coach. Wooden retired from coaching after the 1975 season with a record of 620 wins and 147 losses. His Pyramid of Success, a how-to guide to succeed in all facets of life, is known around the world. Wooden passed away on June 4, 2010, at the age of 99.

Collections support the undergraduate curriculum in the humanities, social sciences, sciences, and mathematics and also include a graphic novel collection, new fiction books, travel guides, and more. Print course reserves are also housed in the library. Events including exhibits, concerts, and historical dances are held in the building's rotunda throughout the year.

results.name: College Library Instructional Computing Commons (CLICC)

Located within CLICC are three electronic learning spaces with desktop stations and laptops, as well as other instructional equipment and services. CLICC offers laptop lending services through which currently enrolled UCLA Students, currently employed UCLA Faculty and staff members may check out a laptop using their UCLA Logon and password.

results.name: Community Bike Center
results.text_description: The UCLA Community Bike Center is a basic service bicycle shop that services all makes and models. Stop by the center to receive a free estimate for your bike. We have everything needed to get your bike running safely and smoothly. Bring your Bruin Card or Recreation Card, your bike, your time, and an inclination to learn. We provide the tools and the advice if you would like to do it yourself or a fee for service if you want us to do the work. The UCLA Community Bike Center also offers rental bikes. Rent one of our Felt Cafe 24 bikes. These bikes have fenders, a rear rack, and a coffee holder attached to the handle bars for all your student/staff/faculty needs. Whether cruising around Westwood, Santa Monica or right here on campus, bikes are a clean, green way to go. Our bikes are available for daily, weekend and weekly rentals. Each bike rental includes a bike lock and helmet. Bike lights are also available for rent at a low cost (front and rear lights are required in the State of California for biking at night...remember safety first!!)

results.name: Counseling and Psychological Services
results.text_description: Whether you're a new arrival to UCLA or a returning Bruin, we'd like to extend a warm welcome to you. Our campus community is diverse in every way imaginable, and engaging with students with different gifts, backgrounds and sensibilities is one of the most exhilarating aspects of life at UCLA. Our diverse counselors and clinicians are knowledgeable in a variety of areas, but we share one core passion: helping students to flourish while pursuing their personal and educational goals. We look forward every Fall to sharing our skills and expertise with you. While the transition to UCLA can be an exciting challenge, we know that some of our students may be coping with personal, financial, health and other stressors. The Counseling Center is here to support your growth and development, and to help you to restore balance, build strength, gain emotional resiliency and increase your personal well-being.

results.name: Court of Philanthropy
results.text_description: Located at the base of Janss Steps, the UCLA Court of Philanthropy recognizes alumni and friends whose generosity will help ensure UCLA's continued excellence. Designed to blend in with the historic architecture at the heart of campus, the donor wall, constructed from Gascone limestone, is inscribed with the names of philanthropists who have donated one million dollars or more.

It also serves as a primary walkway linking the Physical Sciences, Life Sciences and Engineering of the core campus with the Health Sciences campus directly to the south. Surrounding the Court of Sciences are the Math Sciences Building, Franz Hall, the Geology Building, Young Hall, Boyer Hall, Boelter Hall, the new CNSI building, La Kretz Hall, Life Sciences, and the new Orthopedic Hospital Research Center.

Dine indoors, or relax outside surrounded by unique landscaping and the warm California sun. Besides being a beautiful spot on campus to eat, study, and relax with friends, the Court of Sciences Student Center was designed with the environment in mind. The new complex will earn LEED certification through innovative energy conservation techniques and sustainable building practices.

results.name: Dental Clinics
results.text_description: The UCLA School of Dentistry's many general and specialty clinics provide the general public with all dental care needs, from simple cleanings to state-of-the-art repair or replacement of damaged teeth and supporting structures. Patients have a choice of having their care provided by a student dentist, a resident dentist or one of our world-renowned faculty members.

results.name: Department of Earth, Planetary, and Space Sciences
results.text_description: The Department of Earth, Planetary, and Space Sciences, seeks to understand the Earth and the planets. Students, researchers, and faculty tackle a wide range of problems, from the Sun to the most distant planets, and from the center of the Earth to the tenuous ionized gases of the solar wind. We probe the interior of the Earth using seismic data, laboratory measurements, and computer modeling. We study both the ancient tectonics of the Earth and its ongoing activity. We explore Earth's upper atmosphere using spacecraft to measure magnetic fields and plasmas. Moving outward from Earth, we study other planets, their interiors, surfaces, atmospheres, and particle and field environments.

results.name: Department of Microbiology, Immunology and Molecular Genetics
results.text_description: The mission of the UCLA Department of Microbiology, Immunology and Molecular Genetics is to provide the highest quality research and education possible in the interdisciplinary fields of microbiology, immunology and molecular genetics. To meet this goal, the Department works together as scientists, educators and students to identify and address the most relevant problems in microbial pathogenesis and physiology, host cell biology and immune defense, and the host-pathogen interface.

results.name: Department of World Arts and Cultures/Dance
results.text_description: World Arts and Cultures/Dance--the name itself expresses a commitment to cross-cultural understanding through the arts. By looking to world arts, the department seeks to decenter Western perspectives by recognizing that visual and performance arts and other ways of knowing are situated locally and often made and distributed globally. WACD faculty members are interlocutors in dialogues about the frictions and flows implicated by the department's name. As such, WACD is defined by a dynamic interdisciplinary approach that encourages intercultural literacies and repertoires, including and transcending geography, ethnicity, class, and other distinctions of identity. WACD is designed for self-motivated students who want to study the arts in global and local contexts. An internationally renowned faculty provides fresh approaches to arts scholarship and arts practice. Inclusivity is our goal. Students are encouraged to take advantage of resources across campus and in greater Los Angeles, even as they learn from each other.

results.name: Dickson Plaza
results.text_description: Dickson Plaza is perhaps the most photographed area of campus. Featuring an expansive green lawn, Dickson Plaza is situated between Royce and Haines Halls on the north, Powell Library and the Humanities Building on the south, the Flagpole to the east, and the Janss Steps and the Shapiro Fountain to the west. Dickson Terrace is considered the traditional heart of the campus UCLA campus.

results.name: Dirks Pool at Spieker Aquatics Center
results.text_description: This state-of-the-art facility includes a 52-meter by 25-yard all-deep water pool with a bulkhead, allowing competitions to take place at varying distances (meters versus yards). The aquatics center features 3, 5, 7.5, and 10-meter platforms on a diving tower as well as one and three-meter spring boards. This facility is for competitive use only. There is no recreational swimming.

results.name: Disabilities Computing Lab
results.text_description: The DCP Lab houses six PCs and one Mac which are equipped to meet the needs of individuals with vision, mobility and learning impairments. Staff members are available, on a daily basis, to evaluate individuals' specific needs and provide subsequent training in the use of appropriate software. The lab is also open to those needing adaptive software to complete work related tasks.

results.name: Dodd Hall
results.text_description: Dodd Hall, home to the Philosophy, Classics and Art History departments, is named in honor of Paul A. Dodd, former dean of the College of Letters and Science.

results.name: Doris Stein Eye Research Center
results.text_description: Doris Stein, wife of Jules Stein, along with their family and foundation provided funding support for construction of the institute. The area between Jules Stein Eye Institute and Doris Stein Eye Research Center is known as Stein Plaza.

results.name: Drake Track and Field Stadium
results.text_description: Elvin C. "Ducky" Drake spent more than 50 years at UCLA as a student, track coach and head trainer for all athletic teams.

results.name: Dykstra Hall
results.text_description: Clarence Addison Dykstra was chosen provost and vice president of UCLA in 1944. He taught political science on both the Vermont Avenue and Westwood campuses, from 1922-'30.

results.name: East Asian Library
results.text_description: The Richard C. Rudolph East Asian Library was established in 1948 to support UCLA's teaching and research programs in East Asian studies. The library selects, organizes, and makes available Chinese-, Japanese-, and Korean-language materials, and its staff provides reference and instruction services to optimize access to and use of the collections.

results.name: East Melnitz
results.text_description: The East Melnitz Building houses administrative and faculty offices for the School of Theater, Film and Television, and the School of the Arts and Architecture.

results.name: Easton Softball Stadium
results.text_description: UCLA alumnus James L. Easton, CEO and President of sporting goods manufacturer James D. Easton, Inc., donated funds to rebuild the softball stadium. He has also provided financial and equipment support for UCLA sports programs.

results.name: Edward D. and Anna Mitchell Dining Commons
results.text_description: The Edward D. and Anna Mitchell Family Foundation Dining Commons is located on Level 1 of the hospital and is open Monday through Friday, 6:30 a.m. to 10 p.m., and on weekends and holidays from 7:30 a.m. to 8 p.m.

results.name: El Pollo Loco
results.text_description: El Pollo Loco is the nation's leading quick-service restaurant chain specializing in marinated, flame-broiled chicken. El Pollo Loco was first introduced at the Medical Center in 1991 and has captured an important segment of our customer base, providing service to 250,000 customers each year.

results.name: Election Walk
results.text_description: Election Walk occupies the area from the steps in front of Kerckhoff Hall to the Dickson Plaza area between Royce Hall and Powell Library. During Undergraduate Student Association election campaigns, candidates are allowed to put signs on the hillside and distribute literature to students passing by. Students also use the grass knolls near Election Walk to relax throughout the year.

results.name: Engineering 6, Phase 1
results.text_description: Located at the intersection of Westwood Boulevard and Strathmore Avenue, Engineering VI is just steps from Ackerman Student Union, the James West Alumni Center and Pauley Pavilion. Engineering VI is a six-story laboratory building supporting multi-disciplinary energy systems research based on green technology. Laboratories provide temperature-stabilized, low-vibration, and low-electromagnetic environments for the development of alternative energy sources, energy conservation, and energy storage systems. A large roof-top photovoltaic array provides a platform for research in solar technology. Engineering VI is built to LEED Gold standards, the second-highest national environmental ranking for green buildings.

results.name: English Reading Room
results.text_description: The Grace M. Hunt Memorial English Reading Room is a library maintained by the UCLA Department of English that houses approximately 35,000 non-circulating books and periodical volumes in the fields of British and American literature, as well as reference and interdisciplinary sources needed to support these areas of study. Information about the English Reading Room holdings can be found in the UCLA Library Catalog. The collection supports the research and instruction mission of the UCLA Department of English.

results.name: Factor
results.text_description: Philanthropist and former Max Factor Company vice president, Louis Factor was one of four sons of the founder of the international cosmetics firm. He began working in his family's Hollywood plant in his teens, became an industry leader, and upon his retirement in 1973, is said to have known most of the 7,000 employees. He married his childhood sweetheart, Doris, whose gift after her husband's death in 1975 made completion of the building possible.

results.name: Faculty Center
results.text_description: An attractive and comfortable private club, the UCLA Faculty Center offers its members a wide variety of services extending far beyond the traditional noontime meal. The Center is an entirely self-supporting membership organization for UCLA faculty, selected administrative staff and UCLA Alumni members. Its many well furnished meeting rooms, lounges, patios, and dining facilities are available for a wide range of social and professional activities. Members enjoy the relaxing ambiance and make use of their club daily as an intimate gathering place for mingling with colleagues and friends. Banquet services engaged by members for personal or professional occasions meet the highest standards of quality in every detail. All eligible faculty and administrative staff who are not yet members are encouraged to join.

results.name: Faculty Center Member Dining
results.text_description: The UCLA Faculty Center's dining services offer delicious and innovative dishes with the freshest of ingredients. The Coral Patio Grill features waiter service on a lovely tree shaded patio where fresh fish, chicken, and a variety of burgers and scrumptious gourmet sandwiches are prepared to order. Tuesday and Thursday Gourmet Dinners make it easy for you to entertain family and friends or dine with colleagues. Candlelight, linens, flowers, and discreet piano music lend elegance. The moderately priced, four-course dinners include soup, salad, entree, and dessert. Dinners are served year-round from 5:30 p.m. to 8 p.m. The wine list includes many fine California vintages. Full bar services are available. Espresso, cappuccino and gourmet coffees are available in the Playa Lounge during lunch and dinner and cocktails are served from 12 noon. Cocktail Hour, 4 p.m. to 7:30pm, features complimentary hot and cold hors d'oeuvres and full bar service. On chilly days, you'll find a crackling log fire in the hearth.

results.name: Faculty Levering Apartments, 827 Levering
results.text_description: Built in 1983 and purchased in 1987, Faculty Levering is an eight-story, 72-unit, bi-level building located on the corner of Levering and Le Conte, two blocks from campus. The complex has gated parking and is handicapped-accessible. Formerly under the University of California Housing System, this faculty apartment complex was transferred to the Campus Housing System in FY 2013/14 and will continue to be owned and managed by University Apartments. Each unit includes a microwave, stove, refrigerator, dishwasher, garbage disposal, carpeting (some with faux wood flooring), blinds, central heating and air conditioning, campus telephone system, direct Internet connection to the campus backbone, basic cable TV, and 24-hour emergency maintenance. These units were fully renovated in the 1999-2000 fiscal year.

results.name: Family Pool
results.text_description: The Sunset Canyon Family Pool is an outdoor 25-yard pool with a shallow leisure area and adjacent deep water diving well. There are six lap lanes available. Use of this pool is first and foremost for children and students. Patrons may only use the pool during recreational swimming hours.

results.name: Fernald Child Development Center

results.name: Film and Television Archive

It is dedicated to ensuring that the moving image history of our time is explored and enjoyed for generations to come.

results.name: Financial Aid and Scholarships
results.text_description: UCLA Financial Aid and Scholarships professionals will make every effort to help students and their families afford to pay for a UCLA education. The office is dedicated to helping each family create a strategy that works for them. Thanks to the numerous options available, a UCLA education can be affordable.

results.name: Fowler Museum
results.text_description: The Fowler Museum at UCLA is named in honor of Francis E. Fowler Jr., inventor and lifelong art collector. "Reflecting Culture," an exhibit of Fowler's silver collection, is on permanent display. The building also houses the Cotsen Institute of Archaeology. Easy self-service, Pay-by-Space parking is available near the Fowler Museum in Parking Structure 4, accessible from Sunset Boulevard at Westwood Plaza. The complex is located across the street from the western edge of the campus and consists of two-bedroom/two bath furnished units. Each apartment has a microwave, stove, refrigerator, dishwasher, garbage disposal, carpeting, blinds, basic cable TV service, high-speed cable Internet access, and 24-hour emergency maintenance. Kitchens and bathrooms were remodeled to contemporary upgrades with quartz countertops and windows were replaced in summer 2008.

results.name: Geffen Hall
results.text_description: The new six-level, 110,000 square foot Geffen Hall, to be built near the intersection of Le Conte and Tiverton avenues, will allow the David Geffen School of Medicine to expand its educational programs and improve teaching and learning, and the facility is expected to be a boon for recruiting students, staff and faculty. Site preparation is scheduled to begin in September, with building construction to follow. The Teaching and Learning Center, which is expected to be completed in 2016, will feature technology-enabled classrooms to facilitate active learning, a clinical skills training center, innovative and flexible teaching labs that promote collaboration and interaction, as well as spaces for students to relax, room for student organizations to meet, and offices for admissions, financial aid, student affairs and other student services.

The apartment complex amenities include a small exercise room, Wi-Fi hot spots, laundry facilities, central courtyard seating with barbecue, and roof top outdoor lounge. Apartment interior amenities include microwave ovens, stove, refrigerator, dishwasher, garbage disposal, carpeting, vertical blinds, central heating, ceiling fans, basic cable TV service, high-speed cable Internet access, and 24-hour emergency maintenance.

results.text_description: IPAM offers a variety of programs for junior and senior scholars, graduate students and undergraduate students in mathematics, engineering, and a wide range of scientific disciplines in which mathematics may be applied. results.name: Instructional Media Collections and Services
results.text_description: The UCLA Office of Instructional Development (OID) Instructional Media Collections and Services (IMCS) is one of UCLA's central resources for the collection and maintenance of instructional media, providing faculty with thousands of films, DVDs and videos specifically for use in classroom instruction.

results.name: Intramural Playing Fields

results.name: Irma and Norman Switzer Plaza
results.text_description: The UCLA Center for Health Sciences Plaza was renamed to the Irma and Norman Switzer Plaza as a tribute to the couple whose estate bequeathed an unrestricted gift of $50 million to the David Geffen School of Medicine. The bequest will advance medicine and health and will count toward The Centennial Campaign for UCLA, a $4.2 billion fundraising campaign, which was formally launched in May 2014 and is scheduled to conclude in 2019, the campus's 100th year. A veteran of the Korean War, Norman Switzer devised the concept of adding benches to bus stops throughout Los Angeles. In exchange for funding the bus benches, the city awarded his company, Norman Bench Advertising, a 20-year exclusive on advertising. He later sold the business and became a real estate investor. Irma Switzer, an accomplished weaver and member of the Palisades Weavers group, physically built two homes in Manhattan Beach with a friend. The couple was involved with the Fowler Museum at UCLA and the Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County.

During the 1984 Olympic Games, the West Alumni Center served as the athletes' entry-point to the UCLA portion of the Olympic Village.

They were named for the Janss brothers who sold the land that UCLA is built on for about one-third of the going market rate. Leading up from Wilson Plaza to Dickson Court, the Janss Steps have long been a fixture on campus. Before Bruin Plaza became the student activities area, the Janss Steps were often used as an informal assembly area. Speakers at the Steps have included Senator Adlai Stevenson, President John F. Kennedy and Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.

Latte, cappuccino, and other coffee drinks are the specialty of the house. Gourmet pastries fill out the menu, for breakfast on the run or leisurely breaks.

results.text_description: UCLA's first coffee house, opened in 1976, is still a favorite student gathering-place. The leaded glass windows, wood-top tables, and copper counter-front are just some of the details that give the Coffee House its warmth and charm. Coffee drinks are the core of the menu, but there's also an extensive pastry selection and a Baskin-Robbins ice cream counter. For light meals, try the home-made soup or gourmet salads and sandwiches.

results.name: Kerckhoff Hall
results.text_description: Kerckhoff Hall is the only building on campus built in the Collegiate Gothic style. Its pointed arches are in contrast with the rounded Roman arches of the original campus buildings. After success in the lumber business, William G. Kerckhoff was involved in the development of hydroelectric power in 1891, bringing electricity to southern and central California. Kerckhoff and his associates formed the Southern California Gas Corporation in 1910. After his death, Louise honored her husband's wish and donated a generous gift to build and furnish the original student union.

results.name: Kinsey Teaching Pavilion
results.text_description: The Kinsey Teaching Pavilion has three general assignment classrooms (1200B, 1220B and 1240B), all of which are multimedia equipped.

results.name: Kleinrock Internet History Center
results.text_description: KIHC (pronounced ?kick?) is a collaboration between scholars from the Henry Samueli School of Engineering and Applied Science, humanities and social sciences departments, and our philanthropic partners. KIHC was founded in 2012 at UCLA to bring together scholars and students across the university and from other institutions to promote research, teaching, and public interest in the history of the Internet. KIHC encourages research on questions of why the Internet developed into the particular forms we find it in today, and its impacts across the domains of our lives--cultural, economic, political, and more. Working with the UCLA University Archives, the Center is also developing a physical and digital archive focused on documents that exist at UCLA due to its involvement with the ARPANET in the 1960s, 70s, and 80s. UCLA, for instance, was host to one of the original four nodes of the ARPANET, the first global packet-switching based network built by the Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA) to connect users operating from different computer platforms around the U.S. Over the years the four-node network became one of the major foundation of today's Internet. KIHC's documents provide a rich overview of early visions about the Internet's social and economic potential, as told through hand drawings, maps, design sketches, photographs, personal exchanges, and published manuscripts. Drawing from this collection, KIHC's guided tours and revolving exhibits explore the Internet's political and social development into the 21st century, highlighting the collaborative and material nature of the Internet in general.

results.name: Knapp Football Center
results.text_description: The Bud Knapp Football Center is on the first floor, South Wing of the Acosta Center. It houses a large players' locker room that features wood lockers, a new coaches' locker room and an expanded equipment room. Nine position meeting rooms featuring state-of-the-art digital equipment, an auditorium-style team meeting/viewing room and a lobby with trophy display space that highlights the history of the program are also part of the football area.

results.name: Kneller House
results.text_description: Located on Hilgard Avenue directly across from the Guest House, the George F. Kneller residence provides luxury accommodations for upper-level faculty or staff for two years. The unfurnished gated house, built in 1929, consists of four bedrooms, four baths, living room, formal dining room, den, two fireplaces, and a small basement on 1/3 acre with a swimming pool, which was resurfaced in summer 2008, a three-car garage, washer and dryer, basic cable TV service, high-speed cable Internet access, and 24-hour emergency maintenance. The unfurnished house also includes a gas stove, stainless steel refrigerator, microwave, dishwasher, garbage disposal, hardwood floors, vertical blinds, central heating and air conditioning.

results.name: Knudsen Hall
results.text_description: Knudsen Hall was named in honor of Vern Oliver Knudsen, renowned authority in acoustical physics, and UCLA professor beginning in 1922. He was named UCLA chancellor in 1959.

results.name: La Kretz Hall
results.text_description: La Kretz Hall opened in 2005 and features a 352-seat lecture auditorium as well as other instructional spaces. La Kretz Hall is the home of the Institute of the Environment and Sustainability. The building is a model for sustainable resource use, and is the university's first project to receive Silver - New Building certification under the U.S. Green Building Council's Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) rating system.

results.name: Landfair Apartments
results.text_description: The University purchased this property in 1980. Both previously existiing buildings, 558 and 564 Glenrock Avenue, were demolished and redeveloped beginning in January 2013. The newly created building is 558 Glenrock. This new LEED certified, modern undergraduate apartment complex will consist of 171 beds in 48 apartment units with gated parking, featuring two-bedroom and one-bedroom units. The apartment complex amenities include a small exercise room, Wi-Fi hot spots, laundry facilities, central courtyard seating with barbecue, and roof top outdoor lounge. Apartment interior amenities include microwave ovens, stove, refrigerator, dishwasher, garbage disposal, carpeting, vertical blinds, central heating, ceiling fans, basic cable TV service, high-speed cable Internet access, and 24-hour emergency maintenance.

results.name: Landfair Vista Apartments
results.text_description: Landfair Vista is a new complex built in 2013. The University purchased the property in 2013. The undergrad complex is a state-of-the-art building consisting of 169 beds in 37 apartment units, featuring two-bedroom units, two-bedroom with loft units, three-bedroom units, and a three-bedroom with a loft unit. The apartment complex amenities include a central courtyard with free Wi-Fi, central laundry facility and gated parking. Apartment amenities include large windows, microwave, stove, refrigerator, dishwasher, garbage disposal, carpeting, vertical blinds, central heating and air conditioning, gas fireplace, basic cable TV service, high-speed cable Internet access, and 24-hour emergency maintenance. Some units have balconies.

results.name: Law Library
results.text_description: The Hugh and Hazel Darling Law Library is the primary place for study and research for the UCLA School of Law community.

results.name: Lesbian Gay Transgender Campus Resource Center
results.text_description: The UCLA Lesbian Gay Bisexual Transgender Campus Resource Center provides a comprehensive range of education, information and advocacy services and works to create and maintain an open, safe and inclusive environment for lesbian, gay, bisexual, intersex, transgender, queer, questioning, and same-gender-loving students, faculty, and staff, their families and friends, and the entire campus community.

results.name: Lu Valle Commons

He was the founder and first president of the Graduate Students Association. Lu Valle won the bronze medal in the 400 meters in the 1936 Summer Olympics held in Berlin. Lu Valle Commons was dedicated in 1985. Before his death, Lu Valle used to visit the Commons and talk to students there. When introduced, he typically said "Just call me Jimmy." The coffee house there is named "Jimmy's" in tribute to his friendly informality.

Individual Pizza slices are sold in convenient carryout boxes with a variety choice of toppings and a vegetarian option. Lucia's uses only top quality products. results.name: Magnolia Court Apartments

Weyburn Terrace Phase I is a Mediterranean-style apartment complex consisting of 840 furnished and unfurnished studios, two-bedroom/two-bath apartments, and two-bedroom/two-bath townhouses. Each apartment building has a uniquely landscaped courtyard, a common study lounge, a common laundry facility, covered parking and is handicapped accessible. There is a central barbecue area. Each apartment has a kitchen with a refrigerator, stove, microwave, dishwasher, and garbage disposal. In addition, each apartment comes with central heating and air conditioning, unsecured Wi-Fi, campus telephone system, campus basic cable TV, high-speed Internet access, mini blinds, and 24-hour emergency maintenance.

results.text_description: Margan is a four-level building constructed in 1965 and purchased by UCLA in 1990. The undergraduate complex consists of furnished studios, one- and two-bedroom apartments with gated parking, key card entry system, pool and coin-operated laundry. Each apartment has a microwave, stove, refrigerator, dishwasher, garbage disposal, carpeting, blinds, heating and air conditioning, gas fireplace, basic cable TV service, high-speed cable Internet access, and 24-hour emergency maintenance. Kitchens were renovated in 2004, bathrooms were renovated in 2005 and windows were replaced in 2010. Amenities include utilities, basic cable TV service, high-speed cable Internet access, and 24-hour emergency maintenance.

results.name: Marion and Robert S. Wilson Medical Student Lounge
results.text_description: The Marion and Robert S. Wilson Medical Student Lounge opened its doors in the Fall of 1996. This 2,300 square foot lounge is located on the rooftop of the 700 Westwood Plaza Building on the southeast corner of Westwood Boulevard and Circle Drive South. The lounge is for exclusive use of UCLA medical students and is accessible by a card key. Lounge card keys are issued on the third week of the Fall semester. The center contains computer stations, a large area equipped with couches and a large screen television, tables and chairs, a pool table, a microwave oven and sink area, restroom, and an outside patio.

results.name: Marion Anderson Courtyard
results.text_description: The Marion Anderson Courtyard is surrounded by four of the School's six buildings; it is the heart of the UCLA Anderson community and invites personal interaction. Visual corridors to the south and east connect the courtyard to the UCLA campus. A tree-lined creek called Stone Canyon lies to the west.

results.name: Marion Davies Children's Health Center
results.text_description: Marion Davies, motion-picture actress of the late 1920s and early 1930s, donated a major gift in 1952 for completion of the children's clinic in the Center for Health Sciences complex. The project was an outgrowth of the Marion Davies Foundation, a charitable nonprofit corporation through which the star channeled efforts to fight childhood diseases.

results.name: Mattel Children's Hospital
results.text_description: Mattel Children's Hospital UCLA ranks among the world's elite institutions for pediatric research, teaching and care. Serving more than 6,000 inpatients and 100,000 outpatients annually, Mattel Children's Hospital UCLA offers a full spectrum of primary and specialized medical care for infants, children and adolescents. Mattel Children's Hospital UCLA is a vital part of the new Ronald Reagan UCLA Medical Center which continues to be ranked as "Best in the West" by U.S. News & World Report's annual survey of America's hospitals.

You may place a phone order for flowers and take advantage of our free in-hospital delivery service to patients.

The new building design includes a state-of-the-art basketball practice facility dedicated to honoring current and former UCLA Basketball student-athletes; practice gyms for both men's and women's programs; locker rooms for both men's and women's basketball programs; and men's and women's basketball training areas. The facility is named after legendary music industry executive and philanthropist Morris "Mo" Ostin, who generously committed $10 million to the project.

results.name: Morgan Center
results.text_description: JD Morgan led UCLA to 30 NCAA team championships during his 17 years as director of athletic programs. The JD Morgan Center is home to the UCLA Athletic Hall of Fame.

results.name: Murphy Sculpture Garden
results.text_description: One of the most distinguished outdoor sculpture collections in the country, the Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden spans more than five acres in UCLA's campus with over 70 sculptures by artists such as Jean Arp, Deborah Butterfield, Alexander Calder, Barbara Hepworth, Jacques Lipchitz, Henry Moore, Isamu Noguchi, Auguste Rodin, and David Smith. The Franklin D. Murphy Sculpture Garden was dedicated in 1967, after the first acquisitions were installed, including eleven works from the estate of David E. Bright. The Sculpture Garden features over seventy sculptures by artists such as Jean Arp, Alexander Calder, Claire Falkenstein, Barbara Hepworth, Gaston Lachaise, Jacques Lipchitz, Henri Matisse, Henry Moore, Isamu Noguchi, Auguste Rodin, David Smith and Francisco Zuniga, bringing together figural and abstract works and illustrating many approaches to sculpture.

It now plays host to our adult swim lesson program, practices for the Bruin Swim Club, and the American Red Cross safety program. The clinical staff comprises of highly qualified doctors, physician assistants and nurses. Services include: Pre-employment physicals; in-service physical evaluations; diagnosis and treatment of work-related illness and injury; return-to-work examinations and physical evaluations; and immunizations to support health maintenance.

results.name: Organic Garden
results.text_description: The Organic Garden is a plot of land with five 8-foot-by-12-foot raised beds located at the back of Sunset Canyon Recreation Center. Hands-on classes are held at the garden to teach those who wish to learn the basics of how to grow their own fresh fruits, vegetables and herbs in their own backyard gardens, or container gardens. Students learn the basics of seasonal planting, cultivating, harvesting, healthy soil, composting, natural weed and pest management, simple recipes, herb propagation as well as how to make your own teas and infusions.

results.name: Ostin Music Center
results.text_description: Music industry executive and philanthropist Morris "Mo" Ostin donated $10 million to UCLA for the state-of-the-art campus music facility known as the Evelyn and Mo Ostin Music Center. The Ostin Music Center includes a high-tech recording studio, spaces for rehearsal and teaching, a caf? and social space for students, and an Internet-based music production center. Adjacent to the Schoenberg Music Building and the Inverted Fountain, the new structures provide faculty and students access to the latest advances in music technology, research and pedagogy. Over the years, Ostin, who earned his bachelor's degree in economics from UCLA in 1951, and his late wife, Evelyn, who passed away in 2005, have been passionate supporters of the university, most notably in the arts, athletics, medicine and education. In 1998, the Ostins served as co-chairs of the fundraising gala "Royce Hall Encore--Celebrate the Return" after major renovations took place in the famous hall. They were also founders of the UCLA Film and Television Archive Council. A critical part of a music complex that houses the UCLA Herb Alpert School of Music, the Ostin Music Center was designed by Los Angeles-based Daly Genik Architects, under the direction of principal Kevin Daly.

results.name: Powell Library

The beautifully restored building features a 63-foot-high interior dome supported on interlaced trusses with intricately painted ceiling panels. The staff of Resnick Neuropsychiatric Hospital is composed of faculty from the departments of psychiatry, neurology, medicine, pediatrics, as well as members from the professional disciplines of nursing, psychology, occupational therapy, recreational therapy, speech pathology, social work and special education. results.text_description: The Henry Samueli School of Engineering and Applied Science was opened with an enrollment of 379 students in the fall of 1945. It opened as the College of Engineering until it was changed to school on February 21, 1969. The School now has seven academic departments and a total enrollment of more than 4,000 students. It is among the top 10 best engineering schools in public universities nationwide. The School, which is ranked among the top 10 engineering schools at public universities nationwide, offers 28 academic and professional degree programs, including an interdepartmental graduate degree program in biomedical engineering, and is also home to eight major externally funded multimillion-dollar interdisciplinary research centers, in space exploration, wireless sensor systems, nanotechnology, nanomanufacturing and nanoelectronics, as well as many other multidisciplinary ventures.

results.name: Saxon Commons
results.text_description: The Saxon Residential Suites where named after David S. Saxon, who was an American physicist and educator who served as the President of University of California system as well as the Chairman of the Board of Trustees of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology Corporation. Saxon joined UCLA in 1947, but was dismissed in 1950 with thirty other faculty members because of their objection to signing an oath of loyalty and declaration that they were not Communist Party members. He served as the president of University of California between 1975 and 1983. The Saxon Residential Suites were renovated in 2014.

results.name: Student Legal Services
results.text_description: UCLA Student Legal Services provides confidential legal counseling and assistance regarding a wide range of legal issues to all currently registered and enrolled UCLA students. We are able to help with a variety of problems, including: landlord/tenant relations; accident and injury problems; domestic violence and harassment; criminal matters; divorces and other family law matters; automobile purchase, repair, and insurance problems; credit, collections, and financial issues; employment matters; and health care and consumer problems. We also frequently assist students with issues they have with other UCLA departments such as housing, financial aid, harassment, discrimination, ADA compliance, student discipline, and faculty misconduct. We give student the information they need to assess their options and, in appropriate cases, will negotiate on behalf of the student, as well as draft letters and legal documents for the student. Students may make appointments by telephone or in person, and there is a $10 fee for the initial one-hour consultation with an experienced attorney.

Our office provides an online debt management session/entrance exam for all first-time UCLA borrowers that highlight the borrower and lender rights and obligations. We are available to help students with budgeting issues. The Loan Services Office also offers interest-free short-term loans to qualifying, currently registered students with urgent financial need. Exit statements and instructional materials are prepared for all campus-based loan borrowers who drop below half-time status or leave UCLA.

results.text_description: The four-story Westwood Chateau building was built in 1986 and acquired by the University in 1987. Amenities include gated parking, key card entry system, new exercise room, and coin-operated laundry facilities. The building is handicapped accessible. It contains furnished one- and two-bedroom apartments each with a microwave, stove, refrigerator, dishwasher, garbage disposal, carpet, blinds, central heating and air conditioning, gas fireplace, basic cable TV service, high-speed cable Internet access, and 24-hour emergency maintenance. results.text_description: This four-story Mediterranean-style building was built in 1987 and consists of furnished one- and two-bedroom units. The University purchased the property in December 2001. All the units were remodeled in summer of 2012. Windows and sliding balcony doors were replaced with double pane insulated glass on vinyl-framed windows and sliding doors. Each remodeled kitchen and bathroom has a quartz countertop, custom kitchen cabinets, and modern plumbing fixtures. The remodeled bathrooms include new low-flush toilets, glass shower doors with Swanstone bathtub/shower enclosures. The complex features gated subterranean parking, key card entry system, coin-operated laundry rooms, and is handicapped accessible. Each apartment has a microwave, stove, refrigerator, dishwasher, garbage disposal, vertical blinds, heating and air conditioning, gas fireplace, walk-in closet, basic cable TV service, high-speed cable Internet access, and 24-hour emergency maintenance.

results.name: Young Research Library
results.text_description: The Charles E. Young Research Library provides research-level collections and services in the humanities, social sciences, education, public affairs and government information, plus maps, all designed to support graduate students and faculty. Recent renovations have transformed the major public spaces of this classic midcentury design by A. Quincy Jones into a research library for the 21st century. Enhanced facilities offer comfortable, innovative spaces in which to study and conduct research, as well as areas for collaboration, exchange and contemplation.

results.name: Ziman Center for Real Estate
results.text_description: The Richard S. Ziman Center for Real Estate, a joint center of UCLA Anderson School of Management and UCLA School of Law, was formed with a mandate to create and administer UCLA's activities surrounding the topic of real estate. The impetus to establish a new real estate center at UCLA Anderson School of Management was the result of the innovative vision and dedication of John S. Long. In fall 2001, the Center was renamed in recognition of the generosity of Richard S. Ziman, who established its permanent endowment. In fall 2005, the Center was reconstituted as a campus-wide center of both UCLA Anderson School of Management and UCLA School of Law. The Ziman Center currently enjoys the leadership of a 21-member Founding Board comprised of influential leaders from the real estate industry.

results.name: UCLA Anderson
results.text_description: Founded in the depth of the Great Depression, UCLA Anderson School of Management now ranks among the top-tier business schools in the world. An award-winning faculty renowned for research and teaching, highly selective admissions, successful alumni and world-class facilities combine to provide an extraordinary learning environment in the heart of Southern California. UCLA Anderson's faculty comprises outstanding educators and researchers who share their scholarship and expertise in areas such as finance, marketing, accounting, business economics, decision sciences, operations and technology management, human resources and organizational behavior, information systems, and strategy and policy. Leadership themes permeate the curriculum at UCLA Anderson.

results.name: School of Public Health

results.name: Luskin School of Public Affairs
results.text_description: At the convergence of the fields of social work, urban planning, and policymaking, the UCLA Luskin School of Public Affairs identifies and develops emerging areas of research and teaching, cultivating leaders and change agents who advance solutions to society’s most pressing problems. Founded in 1994, UCLA Luskin incorporates the best practices in scholarship, research, and teaching in the fields of social work, urban and regional planning, and policymaking. The unique intersection of these disciplines within one school allows for academic cross-collaboration and a graduate education that values diverse perspectives at the macro- and micro- organizational levels. Graduates of the master’s and doctoral programs are well prepared to take leadership roles and effect change as practitioners, researchers, and policymakers in the public, private, and non-governmental sectors. The School is named after Meyer and Renee Luskin—UCLA alumni, Angelenos, and philanthropists—who generously gave a $100 million gift to UCLA, half of which funded endowments in the School of Public Affairs. On March 18, 2011, the School was officially named the UCLA Meyer and Renee Luskin School of Public Affairs.

results.name: School of the Arts and Architecture
results.text_description: The School of the Arts and Architecture at UCLA (UCLA Arts) plays a vital role in the cultural and artistic life of the campus and the community. Providing a full range of course offerings and programs, the School is comprised of six degree-granting departments: Architecture and Urban Design, Art, Design | Media Arts, Ethnomusicology, Music, and World Arts and Cultures, six centers: the Art | Global Health Center, the Art | Sci Center, the Center for Intercultural Performance, cityLAB, the Experiential Technologies Center and the Grunwald Center for the Graphic Arts, and The UCLA Herb Alpert School of Music, comprising the departments of ethnomusicology, music and musicology.

results.name: Ackerman Union
results.text_description: William Coit Ackerman served as executive director of the Associated Students UCLA (ASUCLA) from 1933 to 1967. Ackerman's association with UCLA spanned 47 years. He was a student (he started at the Southern Branch in 1920), faculty member (physical education), men's tennis coach (his team won the Pacific Coast Conference in 1932 and the NCAA championship in 1950) and ASUCLA official. The student union building, which opened in 1961, was renamed Ackerman Union upon "Mr. A's" retirement in 1967. The five-level building includes food services, financial offices, a ballroom for special events, study lounges, recreational areas, direct services, and a student store.
